        "body1": "With free agency fully slowed down, the draft will start to gain even more attention this week. Locally in Michigan, both Michigan State and the University of Michigan have their Pro Days this week -- as do many other schools around the country.\n\nWith the Detroit Lions holding the No. 21 pick in the draft, they are going to start to look heavily at what prospects might fit them best for the end of April. With that in mind, we take today\u2019s Lions Mailbag question.\n\nTo ask a future Mailbag question, use the hashtag #LionsMailbag on Twitter, email me at michael.rothstein@espn.com or follow along on Facebook and ask there.\n\nNow, on to today\u2019s question.\n\n@mikerothstein if your bob Quinn who and what position do you address first in the Draft #Lionsmailbag \u2014 \u303dichigan vs Nation (@AndrewBuris) March 20, 2017\n\nAndrew,\n\nThe easiest answer here is the best player available at a position of need -- so basically anywhere other than quarterback or offensive line. That said, there are spots on the Lions' roster that are needier than others.\n\nThe good thing for the Lions is the draft is deep on the defensive line, at linebacker and at cornerback, so if a high-level player at another position happens to slip in the draft and is sitting there at No. 21, Detroit could make that move and still pick up quality players at key positions in later rounds. For instance, it would be highly surprising if a receiver like Mike Williams or a running back like Leonard Fournette fell to No. 21. If they did, the Lions might consider them -- same with Alabama tight end O.J. Howard if he\u2019s around at No. 21.\n\nProvided those things don\u2019t happen, figure the Lions are going to look at a player who can be an upgrade on defense -- either as a pass-rusher or a do-it-all linebacker. This, though, is where names will differ. Among the defensive linemen, Tennessee\u2019s Derek Barnett, Missouri\u2019s Charles Harris and Michigan's Taco Charlton would be good fits as pass-rushing defensive ends. The Lions will likely also do their research on Michigan State defensive tackle Malik McDowell.\n\nAt linebacker, Temple\u2019s Haason Reddick is a popular choice at No. 21 as a three-down linebacker who can be a playmaker on the weak side -- the position vacated by the release of DeAndre Levy. He would probably compete with free agent Paul Worrilow for that role -- or maybe another former Temple linebacker, Tahir Whitehead.\n\nUCLA\u2019s Takkarist McKinley, Alabama\u2019s Tim Williams, Wisconsin\u2019s T.J. Watt, Florida\u2019s Jarrad Davis, Ohio State\u2019s Raekwon McMillan and Vanderbilt\u2019s Zach Cunninham all could be in play as well, either in the first round or the second for Detroit. That\u2019s how deep the linebacker group is this year.\n\nThere\u2019s also the chance Detroit could make a move in its secondary since cornerback Nevin Lawson and safeties Glover Quin and Tavon Wilson are all in contract years. Ohio State\u2019s Gareon Conley and Alabama\u2019s Marlon Humphrey could be intriguing cornerback options at No. 21, particularly if the Lions think there\u2019s more depth in the front seven to be had later on. Adoree Jackson, a cornerback/returner from USC, is a name to watch -- not necessarily at No. 21 but he could be a good fit in the second round.\n\nThen there\u2019s one of the most versatile players in the draft, Michigan safety Jabrill Peppers. If he\u2019s available at No. 21, the Lions almost have to at least take a look at him. Peppers can provide an immediate boost to the return game and would be an interesting piece for defensive coordinator Teryl Austin to use. The issue there would be that he fits a similar role, defensively, to how the Lions use Miles Killebrew. But with their own safeties heading toward a potential season of flux in 2018 and Peppers able to play multiple positions, as he did at Michigan, he might warrant consideration.", 
        "body0": "Martin Johnson says Alun Wyn Jones should skipper the British and Irish Lions in New Zealand. Video courtesy of Standard Life Investments\n\nMartin Johnson said on current form Wales' Alun Wyn Jones is the man to lead the British and Irish Lions in June.\n\nJones took up the Wales captaincy after Sam Warburton stepped down ahead of the Six Nations, and Johnson has backed the 116-cap international to lead the Lions in New Zealand.\n\n\"As the tournament has gone on I just thought Alun Wyn Jones has played really well,\" said Johnson. \"Right now if you're picking a Test team I'd pick him in the second row and I'd pick him as captain. That would by my choice.\"\n\nJohnson - the only man to captain the Lions in two series - says the competitive nature of this year's Six Nations will ensure Warren Gatland has plenty to ponder ahead of his Lions squad announcement on April 19, particularly in the pack.\n\n\"I think he's got some really tough calls,\" said Johnson. \"Like anything there's obviously some guys who are in the 'definites', some guys in the 'highly likelys', the 'probables', and there's a bunch that you're going to have to pick the rest from - the 'possibles'.\n\n\"There was a lot of talk about Jonny Gray and numbers, but I think Richie Gray had more impact. He's a more mature player than he was four years ago.\" Martin Johnson on second row selections for the Lions\n\n\"I think a No 8 like Billy Vunipola will go, but who else will go? [Taulupe] Faletau has not played that much in the Six Nations but we know he's a quality player, and then there's some young guys like Ross Moriarty.\"\n\nThe 47-year-old says second row is an area of particularly acute competition for places in the squad.\n\n\"I think Alun Wyn Jones for me has nailed one down, I think Maro Itoje has nailed one down.\n\n\"Richie Gray for me was the best Scottish second row - there was a lot of talk about Jonny Gray and numbers, but I think Richie Gray had more impact. He's a more mature player than he was four years ago.\"\n\nAlun Wyn Jones led the Lions to victory in the third Test of the 2013 series\n\nThe 10-game tour of New Zealand represents the biggest challenge these players will ever face, says Johnson, but urged those involved to write their names in the history books.\n\n\"The challenge is the biggest in rugby, simple as that. New Zealand are always very good - that goes back from the dawn of rugby time.\n\n\"Win a series down there, you go with the immortals straight away in a very special group of players. It's worth the effort, it's worth the sacrifice to put everything into that six or seven weeks.\"\n\nSir Ian McGeechan says Sam Warburton should be picked as Lions captain\n\nThe players will no longer have a chance to showcase their credentials on the international stage, as the Six Nations concluded in thrilling fashion in Dublin on Saturday.\n\nEngland's hopes of a tier one record of 19 consecutive Test victories were halted by Ireland at the Aviva Stadium, with Joe Schmidt's side winning 13-9 to finish second in the championship.\n\n\"The nature of Ireland's performance I don't think would have been any surprise to anyone, that's how they're going to play,\" said Johnson.\n\n\"They can handle the wet weather - they played like that against France - they're going to play with a huge amount of passion; you have to take that away from them and force them into errors.\n\nJohnson says England will learn from their loss to Ireland in Dublin\n\n\"It was a typical Six Nations game. Those games have been happening since before I was even playing the game. It's nice that things don't change but it was disappointing from England's point of view.\"\n\nThe 2003 World Cup winner says England will learn from the loss and benefit from it in the long term.\n\n\"If you're winning two consecutive Grand Slams everything's fine - you do need to sometimes be brought back down to earth.\n\n\"I said before the game it's a survivable loss for England, they're still going to be champions - and even if they weren't, it's survivable.\"", 
        "body2": "The auditions are almost over. Time to select the cast. It\u2019s time for Warren Gatland to retreat to the bunker at the end of the garden, sharpen his pencil, find the big notepad and draw up his final squad to beat the most dominant team in sporting history.\n\nThe British & Irish Lions coach has one day short of a month to pick his touring side. He has watched the contenders beat seven bells out of each other for the last month, some will have risen in his expectations, some fallen. But who is in contention to be selected on April 19? Here we look at the runners and riders for the most daunting task in sport \u2013 beating New Zealand at least twice on their own paddock this summer.\n\nOf course there are vital European Champions Cup matches to come, and several stars may suffer the crushing blow of last-minute injuries or tour-busting bans, but as it stands these are the men in contention for each position.\n\nWarren Gatland has until April 19 to make his selections for the Lions tour of New Zealand\n\nFULL-BACK\n\nStuart Hogg has played his way into \u2018dert-cert\u2019 territory here with Welsh duo Leigh Halfpenny and Liam Williams probably fighting it out for one spot behind him.\n\nThe case to pick 2013 Lions man of the series Halfpenny is boosted by the presence of Neil Jenkins as the kicking coach for this tour \u2013 but the Toulon man is nowhere near as good as he was four years ago. Can you beat the All Blacks with him at full-back?\n\nWilliams has played on the left wing exclusively for Wales in the Six Nations, but really is a better full-back so should be considered there. His was also brilliant in the tour to New Zealand last summer, even if Wales lost 3-0.\n\nRob Kearney could force his way onto a third tour but probably needs a few stunning games for Leinster to make it \u2013 he would be a safe pick and is far more assured as a bomb-disposing expert than the others when the high-balls rain down. Mike Brown\u2019s chances look slimmer by the match.\n\nStuart Hogg appears to be one of the certainties to be picked on the Lions tour\n\nWING\n\nA plethora of options here. You may as well carve George North and Elliot Daly\u2019s names in stone now \u2013 Daly has been the find of the last six months and can play three positions so would be a perfect No 23 in the Test squad. North is sure to go. Even if he had not come back into form he would have made it \u2013 his impending battle with Julian Savea will echo the war with Israel Folau from the Australia tour, two behemoths battering into each other. Excellent.\n\nElsewhere you have flyers and grafters. In the former category put Simon Zebo, Anthony Watson, Jonny May and Sean Maitland, the latter Tommy Seymour, Jack Nowell and Keith Earls \u2013 there will be a smattering of both. Tim Visser probably won\u2019t make it as a North mark II figure \u2013 he probably does not offer enough other than finishing.\n\nAnd what about Christian Wade? Under-appreciated by England, toured in 2013 and always scores tries \u2013 could he be a left-field shout? His defence may be his downfall though.\n\nElliot Daly starred for England during the Six Nations and is a long-range kicking option\n\nCENTRE\n\nJonathan Joseph is not only the best attacking No 13 in the northern hemisphere at the moment, he is the best defensive one too. He goes. And if we are classing Owen Farrell as an inside centre, then he is even more certain to go in this slot than his English outside man.\n\nSo who\u2019s left? Alex Dunbar gave a strong impression of a revolving door against England so his application has found its way into the round filing cabinet, his Scottish partner Huw Jones could be a bolter, but probably won\u2019t be.\n\nThat\u2019s a similar scenario for 22-year-old Garry Ringrose \u2013 good in parts, not good enough in others. When picking a Lions tour squad youth should be trumped by the ace-card experience \u2013 there is no future planning here, only the best can go.\n\nRobbie Henshaw is an odd one. He was pretty much perfect against New Zealand in the Chicago win, but alarmingly looked powerless and one-dimensional against the Welsh red wall of defence in Cardiff. A huge hitter though and will tour.\n\nThen it\u2019s another Welsh shootout. Gatland will probably have to pick between Scott Williams and Jonathan Davies \u2013 neither ripped up trees in the Six Nations and Wales scored just eight tries in five games with them at the creative controls. At the moment he would probably plump for Davies, but it\u2019s tight.\n\nJonathan Joseph's attacking capabilities came to the fore for England in recent weeks\n\nFLY-HALF\n\nNo arguments about two slots here, loads about the other one. Jonathan Sexton and Owen Farrell are probably the two most important players for this prospective Lions squad \u2013 the questions over whether they can play together or if they will be rugby\u2019s equivalent of a Steven Gerrard and Frank Lampard combination can wait, barring injury they are the first two names typed onto the squad announcement press-release.\n\nThen it is a question of George Ford, Dan Biggar, Finn Russell. You would probably only take one of those. Russell is the maverick choice, but in games against England and for Glasgow against Munster he blotted his copybook leaving an indelible mark. Too much of a risk. Biggar is maybe the Sexton-lite \u2013 hard, consistent, demanding of others but not as influential as the Irishman. Ford has formed half of the most potent European playmaking partnership in recent times, but can be targeted in defence.\n\nThese are ones that come down to personal preference rather than necessarily who is the best player. Let\u2019s go for Ford then, remembering that Biggar will be in Auckland touring the Pacific with Wales, so is only an uber away from the Lions hotel\u2026\n\nOwen Farrell has been shortlisted for Six Nations player of the tournament\n\nSCRUM-HALF\n\nOk, this is easy. Conor Murray \u2013 controlling master. Rhys Webb \u2013 rapid wind-up merchant. Tick, tick. The less easy pick is the third and final slot.\n\nGreig Laidlaw? Probably not \u2013 we won\u2019t hold his tweed waistcoat, as displayed on ITV for the England match, against him, he is probably not quite good enough to tour. Injury may also play against him.\n\nBen Youngs? Danny Care? One of two you feel. Care would provide more as a \u2018finisher\u2019, sorry, substitute \u2013 blame Eddie \u2013 but is Youngs the better player and more likely to cover for Murray like he did four years ago? I reckon so. Care\u2019s kicking from hand is an issue that cannot be swept under the carpet.\n\nRhys Webb is one of those in contention but will have to impress in midweek matches\n\nPROP\n\nRight, two pairs need to go here. Jack McGrath and Tadhg Furlong have stormed onto the international stage \u2013 particularly Furlong, who was immense against the All Blacks last November and is the best young tight-head in the world.\n\nJoe Marler and Dan Cole should also make it \u2013 their scrummaging power and work around the field is very strong. You would imagine they would both be \u2018good tourists\u2019 too. Add Mako Vunipola to that \u2013 the best ball-playing front-rower in the world \u2013 and you have a strong set.\n\nAnd as the Lions go through props more quickly than their fans will pints of beer on tour, Gatland is likely to boost the numbers with 21-year-old Zander Fagerson, with the likes of Kyle Sinckler, Rob Evans, Samson Lee, Cian Healy and WP Nel (if fit in time) told to keep their eye in at the gym in case of inevitable late call-ups.\n\nTadhg Furlong (left) and Jack McGrath (right) have burst onto the scene for Ireland\n\nHOOKER\n\nAnd so to an area of controversy. England captains have a recent habit of missing Lions tours. Chris Robshaw was discarded from the last one after the 30-3 mauling by Wales on the final day of the 2013 Six Nations, and Dylan Hartley may be the next.\n\nIt would be a big call \u2013 this is a man who has lost just once when leading his country, who are clearly the best of the Lions nations. But Jamie George is an itch that needs to be scratched. Surely the Saracens man is so good he cannot be overlooked? Could he even play for the Lions before he starts for England? It has been done before \u2013 Will Greenwood completed that feat in 1997.\n\nAnd what about \u2018Cannonball\u2019 Ken Owens? Nominated for Six Nations player of the Championship, the Welshman is combative and strong in the set-piece.\n\nThen there is Rory Best \u2013 the only current captain to have beaten New Zealand. Is his lineout throwing reliable enough?\n\nRory Best faces some stiff competition at hooker with Dylan Hartley and Jamie George options\n\nSECOND-ROW\n\nThe problem here is too many options. Unfortunately you cannot realistically take 11 locks, so some huge names will miss out in this department.\n\nAlun Wyn Jones is a cast-iron tourist. Maro Itoje and Joe Launchbury too. But then Courtney Lawes has been staggeringly good and George Kruis was monumental before injury \u2013 that is just the English.\n\nIain Henderson is a star who can also play at No.6, Donncha Ryan seems carved out of stone.\n\nThe fact that neither of the brothers Gray \u2013 Richie and Jonny \u2013 may make the tour shows the remarkable strength in this area.\n\nOh, and then there is Jake Ball and Luke Charteris. What to do!?\n\nAlun Wyn-Jones has been touted as a potential captain but was injured against France\n\nBACK-ROW\n\nNearly there! This is an area full of stars, and again, some monumental players will have to watch from 12,000 miles away. We all know about Billy Vunipola, Taulupe Faletau and Sam Warburton \u2013 they are all on the plane, no worries. But then it is all about balance \u2013 Justin Tipuric is probably the only proper \u2018seven\u2019 available \u2013 someone who has great hands, is fast, agile and turns over ball at the breakdown, so he will go too.\n\nThen it is a list of bashers. CJ Stander \u2013 a giant. Ross Moriarty \u2013 a colossus. James Haskell \u2013 a warrior. Sean O\u2019Brien \u2013 the Tullow tank.\n\nAnd then what about Peter O\u2019Mahony? He was such a mammoth against England that it is hard to leave him in Cork.\n\nBilly Vunipola returned early from injury and gives Warren Gatland another back row option\n\nJamie Heaslip may have to pray for injuries to make a third tour, Nathan Hughes too. Tom Wood and Chris Robshaw may be crushed by lack of game-time, both would never let you down though.\n\nWhat of some Scots too? John Barclay, John Hardie, Ryan Wilson, Hamish Watson? You might squeeze Watson in if you feel there are too many blind-sides on the A380 aeroplane south.\n\nWherever you look there are so many good players \u2013 but who will make it? A month to finalise the squad. Gatland will probably not pick more than 38 players, he has said as much himself.\n\nMake no mistake \u2013 if the Lions win in New Zealand it will be one of the great sporting achievements of all time. The schedule, the time together, the opposition, the country, all those records \u2013 it\u2019s a daunting task.\n\nGatland better get it right then, and he has a month of scribbling in the shed left.\n\nHamish Watson is one of those with an outside chance at being selected on the tour\n\nMY LIONS SQUAD TO TOUR NEW ZEALAND\n\nFORWARDS (21)\n\nProps: Mako Vunipola, Joe Marler, Jack McGrath, Tadhg Furlong, Dan Cole, Zander Fagerson\n\nHookers: Dylan Hartley, Ken Owens, Jamie George\n\nLocks: Alun Wyn Jones \u00a9, Maro Itoje, Joe Launchbury, Courtney Lawes, George Kruis\n\nBack row: CJ Stander, James Haskell, Sam Warburton, Justin Tipuric, Ross Moriarty, Billy Vunipola, Taulupe Faletau\n\nBACKS (17)\n\nScrum-halves: Conor Murray, Rhys Webb, Ben Youngs\n\nFly-halves: Jonathan Sexton, George Ford\n\nCentres: Owen Farrell, Robbie Henshaw, Jonathan Joseph, Jonathan Davies\n\nWings: George North, Elliot Daly, Simon Zebo