        "body1": "Nile Ranger A lot of harsh words were said after the Bristol Rovers game and we put it right tonight. From minute one to minute ninety-three, it summed up what we were talking about.\n\nCoventry City 0 Southend United 2\n\nSky Bet League One\n\nBy Rowland Lyons at the Ricoh Arena\n\nPhil Brown got the perfect response on Tuesday night, after Southend bounced back from a poor weekend defeat, as first-half Nile Ranger and Ryan Leonard strikes kept their play-off hopes alive.\n\nThe Shrimpers were on the front foot straight from the start, with Anthony Wordsworth going close after only 17 seconds.\n\nBut, the visitors soon got their noses in front, when Ranger started the move that ended with Theo Robinson shrugging off his marker and playing in his strike partner, who picked his spot with a second-minute side-footer.\n\nThe Shrimpers continued to ask all the questions and it was no surprise that they increased their lead on 23 minutes. Wordsworth\u2019s short free-kick saw Leonard let fly from 25 yards with a deflected effort that was still rising as it beat the helpless Ryan Burge.\n\nIt what was almost total one-way traffic, Coventry\u2019s token response came from an off- target Nathan Clarke header, before Ranger continued to torment the home defence, with the former Orient stopper, Clarke, working overtime.\n\nThe second-half was an almost total non-event with Southend\u2019s Ted Smith saving a weak 49th minute Callum Reilly effort, before John White did well to block a close-range Reilly effort in the closing stages.\n\nBrown said: \"A lot of harsh words were said after the Bristol Rovers game and we put it right tonight. From minute one to minute ninety-three, it summed up what we were talking about.\"\n\n\"Making the five changes tonight spiked the players. You have to say John White, Ryan Inniss, Stephen McLaughlin, Nile Ranger and Theo Robinson came in to join players who had been playing consistently well for twenty-five games. It was a good squad performance.\"\n\nBrown added: \"I have just watched the (first) goal and it was reminiscent of Nile Ranger when he played at Sheffield United, when Theo Robinson showed what he could do - dispossessing the centre-half as if he wasn\u2019t there, and laid a perfect pass on for Nile to net with a first-class, top drawer finish.\"\n\nBrown claimed: \"I\u2019ve got a big enough squad to make changes. Leaving the likes of Timlin and Demetriou back at home and being able to bring on the likes of McGlashan and Nouble, bodes well for Saturday.\"\n\n\"You look at Ryan Leonard. He ran his heart out. He got himself a goal. But he\u2019s wearing tape on his hamstring - and I\u2019ve really got to look at him regarding Saturday. One: if he\u2019s got the energy and two: to understand what Walsall\u2019s system brings to the party.\"\n\nMatchwinner Leonard said: \"We wanted to put last Saturday\u2019s result right tonight - as that (performance) was no where near good enough.\"\n\n\"It was a great start, with Wordsworth skimming the post inside the first thirty seconds. Then we got the first and then the second - and then we saw the game out quite comfortably.\"\n\nLeonard was entitled to be happy with his goal: \"I don\u2019t score bad ones, do I? It was nice to get the second, as it gave us that little bit of a cushion. We then defended well at the end - as Coventry pushed a lot of bodies forward. - with John White making a great block at the end.\"\n\nThe midfielder concluded: \"I thought we at least repaid our fans tonight, especially after last Saturday. We got the result - it was for them, really.\"\n\nSouthend entertain Walsall this Saturday (kick-off 3pm).\n\nThe teams:\n\nCoventry City: Burge, Farrend Rawson, Nathan Clarke, Jordan Turnbull (Kwame Thomas 46), Dion Kelly-Evans, Garend Birigama (George Thomas 62), Ben Stevenson, Callum Reilly, Marcus Tudgay, Stuart Beavon.\n\nSubs: Reice Charles-Cook (gk), Chris Stokes, Ruben Lameiras, Kyel Reid, Vladimir Gadzhev.