ale on Tuesday night.\n\nThus far in his second managerial stint at the club, Robins has presided over three defeats, scoring no goals and conceding five.\n\nBut that only tells a quarter of the story.\n\nThat win percentage - of 0 - equals that of Tony Mowbray, who oversaw no victories from his 10 matches in charge of the Sky Blues at the start of the campaign.\n\nWhat did Robins say?\n\nMark Robins admits that his Coventry City players are not fit or savvy enough for the rigours of League One football.\n\nThe Sky Blues boss saw his newly-inherited side slip to their third consecutive defeat under his charge with a narrow 1-0 loss at MK Dons, a result that left him saddened by the team\u2019s plight and questioning the work they have been doing on the training ground all season.\n\n\u201cI think it was better,\u201d said the City manager, \u201cbut we\u2019re not fit enough, don\u2019t get around the pitch for 90 minutes and at times that will cost us.\n\n\u201cWe are where we are and it\u2019s very sad.\n\n\"There is some decent talent here.\n\n\"We started off OK and the belief will start to come back if we keep playing in that manner and try to drive.\n\n\"We ended up getting closer to their box \u2013 and I know it was ironic cheers from the fans, and I get that \u2013 but at least we\u2019re trying to get in their penalty area and create things.\n\n\"But the pressure and momentum doesn\u2019t build because we run out of steam.\u201d\n\nWhat did the fans say?\n\n\"Serious question. When did we last win in the league?\" asked one fan.\n\nAnother added: \"Can we not just throw in the towel now? Let's prepare for League Two.\"\n\n908 fans made the trip to Buckinghamshire to cheer on the Sky Blues, but were left disappointed in grim weather and headed home empty handed.\n\n\"Left early,\" one fan admitted on Twitter, before adding: \"Can't watch any more #heartbreaking.\"\n\nMany more fans had their say on Twitter and we have collected some of the reaction from soc